text.paragraph:
Limited data with Metformin Hydrochloride in pregnant women are not sufficient to determine a drug-associated risk for major birth defects or miscarriage. Published studies with metformin use during pregnancy have not reported a clear association with metformin and major birth defect or miscarriage risk [see 
                                 Error! Hyperlink reference not valid.
                                 ]. There are risks to the mother and fetus associated with poorly controlled diabetes mellitus in pregnancy [see 
                                 Error! Hyperlink reference not valid.
                                 ].

No adverse developmental effects were observed when metformin was administered to pregnant Sprague Dawley rats and rabbits during the period of organogenesis at doses up to 2-and 5times, respectively, a 2550 mg clinical dose, based on body surface area [see 
                                 Error! Hyperlink reference not valid.
                                 ].

Limited published studies report that metformin is present in human milk [see 
                                 Error! Hyperlink reference not valid.
                                 ]. However, there is insufficient information to determine the effects of metformin on the breastfed infant and no available information on the effects of metformin on milk production. Therefore, the developmental and health benefits of breastfeeding should be considered along with the mother's clinical need for Metformin Hydrochloride and any potential adverse effects on the breastfed child from Metformin Hydrochloride or from the underlying maternal condition.
